namespace anthill.prelude
{< Type: the type of types in the kernel ŌĆö an OPAQUE, term-backed handle.

   WI-361 (representation convergence): a `Type` value IS an ordinary term ŌĆö
   `Ref(S)` for a bare sort, `Fn{S, named}` for a parameterized type, with a
   value-in-type carried as `TypeExtractor.Denoted` and the structural forms
   (arrow / named tuple / effects row / nothing / type var) carried as the
   `TypeExtractor.*` entities (below). There is NO stored deep ADT inside
   `Type`; its structure is REIFIED on demand by
   `anthill.reflect.extract(t) -> TypeExtractor`.

   So `Type` is a bare `sort Type = ?` ŌĆö an opaque handle like `Term` /
   `Symbol` ŌĆö and every structural form lives in `TypeExtractor`. `Eq` /
   `Lattice` ride Type's NOMINAL identity (NOT `Term`'s ŌĆö keying the
   type-lattice on `Term` would make it the universal default on every term,
   so the resolver could not tell a type-term from any term by structure). The
   namespace-level facts below scope the lattice/eq to `Type` alone (the
   carrier is derived from the `T = Type` binding).

   `Type` and `EffectExpression` remain *co-defined* in this file:
   EffectExpression's element forms (`present` / `absent` / `open`) carry a
   `Type`, and the effects-row structural form (`TypeExtractor.EffectsRows`)
   carries an EffectExpression. Splitting them across files created a
   cross-file import cycle whose soundness depended on the loader's 2-pass
   scan; colocating them removes the cycle. >}
  sort Type = ?

  -- Type forms a lattice via entity_of / refines (no top ŌĆö the lattice is
  -- unbounded above; Nothing is the bottom). `Eq` / `Lattice` ride Type's
  -- nominal identity (WI-361). These are namespace-level facts, so the
  -- provides-carrier is derived from the `T = Type` binding value (ŌåÆ Type);
  -- short names resolve as `anthill.prelude` siblings (a qualified
  -- `anthill.prelude.Type` is not accepted in binding-value position).
  fact PartialEq[T = Type]      -- WI-644: Eq requires the PartialEq base
  fact Eq[T = Type]
  fact Lattice[T = Type]
end

{< Concat[A, B]: the TYPE-position surface of a schema merge (WI-714 / proposal 052 ŌĆö
   `join`'s merged schema `T = Concat[A = r1.T, B = r2.T]`). A type constructor, so it
   is writable where a type is expected (a signature's return type); it names the
   concatenation of two NAMED-TUPLE types ŌĆö `A`'s fields followed by `B`'s.

   Concat is INERT as written and carries no values: like `Type`, it has NO entities, so
   a `Concat[..]` is never a runtime value ŌĆö it only NAMES a merge. The typer performs
   that merge as an INTERNAL type-level operation: `Concat[A = nt1, B = nt2]` REDUCES to
   the single named tuple concatenating the two operands' fields, at the same
   normalization boundary the `s.T` projection is eliminated (`reduce_concat_in_type` in
   kb/typing.rs, sharing `concat_named_tuple_types`). This is the projection precedent ŌĆö
   `ExprCarried` is a type FORM, `project_type_member` its internal reduction; `Concat`
   is the form, the merge its reduction.

   SCOPE: `Concat` reduces only as a DIRECT type argument (the schema position
   `Relation[T = Concat[A = .., B = ..]]`). Each of the following is a LOUD error ŌĆö
   deferred to a follow-up, never a silent skip: a field-name collision; a non-named-tuple
   operand (a 1-collapse / membership schema); and a `Concat` nested in any other carrier
   (a tuple field, an arrow, an effect row).

   ABSTRACT OPERANDS (WI-734) ŌĆö settled once for the whole ctor family (`Concat`,
   `Without`, and any later member): an operand that is NOT YET KNOWN leaves the ctor
   SYMBOLIC rather than raising, to reduce later once the operand grounds. "Not yet known"
   means a logic VARIABLE ŌĆö the skolem an enclosing generic op's `[S]` becomes, or an
   unsolved inference var ŌĆö or an unreduced residual one level down. So a generic wrapper
   over abstract relation schemas IS expressible: `merge(a, b)` inside
   `[L, R](a: Relation[T = L], b: Relation[T = R]) -> Relation[T = Concat[A = L, B = R]]`
   type-checks, and the residual reduces at the concrete call. An operand that IS known but
   cannot be merged stays a LOUD error ŌĆö "cannot reduce yet" and "cannot reduce ever" are
   different answers and no longer share one diagnostic.

   CONFLUENCE: a residual exists only over an un-instantiated operand, so a fully concrete
   type is always fully reduced ŌĆö there are never two comparable forms of one concrete
   type. CAVEAT: the reduction gate reads an op's DECLARED return type, so a generic
   wrapper must PROPAGATE the ctor in its own signature (as `join` / `fix` do); widening to
   a bare `Relation` lets the residual escape unreduced. That escape is SAFE rather than a
   silent wrong schema ŌĆö an unreduced ctor offers no named-tuple schema, so any column use
   on it fails LOUDLY at dot dispatch. Widening costs usability, never correctness. >}
sort anthill.prelude.Concat
  sort A = ?
  sort B = ?
end

{< Without[T, Drop]: the TYPE-position surface of a schema DROP (WI-727 / proposal 056 ŌĆö
   `fix`'s narrowed schema `T = Without[T = p.T, Drop = R]`). The DUAL of `Concat`: where
   `Concat` merges two named tuples, `Without` removes from named tuple `T` every field
   whose name is a field of the record `Drop`. Prior art: TypeScript `Omit<T, K>` (as
   `Concat`/project mirror `&`/`Pick`).

   Like `Concat`, `Without` is INERT and carries no values ŌĆö it only NAMES a drop. The
   typer performs it as an INTERNAL type-level operation: `Without[T = nt, Drop = r]`
   REDUCES to the named tuple `nt` minus `r`'s fields, at the same normalization boundary
   `Concat` / the `s.T` projection reduce (`reduce_without_in_type` in kb/typing.rs, sharing
   `without_named_tuple_types`). The residual 1-collapses (element / `Unit`) as any relation
   schema does.

   `Drop` is the record produced by a variadic argument CAPTURE (`...args: R`, ┬¦2.1), so it
   stays UNCONSTRAINED at the capture site ŌĆö the MEANING is supplied HERE: a `Drop` field
   naming no `T` field, or one whose (captured) type mismatches its column, is a LOAD error
   in the reduction (┬¦2.2). An empty `Drop` (`r.fix()`, an empty capture) is the identity.

   SCOPE: `Without` reduces only as a DIRECT type argument (the schema position
   `Relation[T = Without[T = .., Drop = ..]]`) over a CONCRETE named tuple `T`. A `Drop`
   naming no column, a type mismatch, a non-named-tuple `T` (a 1-collapse / membership
   schema, which has no named column to drop by), and a `Without` nested in any other
   carrier are each a LOUD error ŌĆö deferred, never a silent skip.

   ABSTRACT OPERANDS (WI-734): `Without` follows the family rule stated on `Concat` above
   ŌĆö an operand that is not yet known (a logic variable, or an unreduced residual) leaves
   the ctor symbolic to reduce once it grounds, while a KNOWN but undroppable operand
   stays loud. `p.fix(name: "a")` on a `p: Relation[T = S]` with `S` abstract therefore
   type-checks instead of reporting the 1-collapse diagnostic against a type parameter. >}
sort anthill.prelude.Without
  sort T = ?
  sort Drop = ?
end

{< EffectExpression: the effect-row carried by an arrow (proposal 045 ┬¦3, ┬¦6).

   The surface algebra a programmer writes ŌĆö `present` / `absent` / `open`
   tail / `merge` / `empty_row` (`{}`) ŌĆö which is *also* the stored representation:
   it replaces `Type.arrow`'s `effects : List[Type]`. Its **normal form**
   (the present labels + an optional row-variable tail + the `absent`/`lacks`
   constraints, with `merge`s flattened) is "the row" the typer unifies
   (045 ┬¦5), so surface and row are one sort, not two.

   A row-variable tail (`open`) reuses the typer's type-variable substrate
   (`Type.type_var`), so effect polymorphism and propagation are ordinary
   unification of that variable (045 ┬¦5.1) ŌĆö not a bespoke scheme. This is
   the row-polymorphism design (R├®my 1989; Lindley & Cheney 2012); the prior
   `EffectSet` specialization of `Set` (ACI matching) is **removed**
   (2026-05-28), superseded by this sort (045 ┬¦6).

   Co-defined with `Type` above (WI-320, 2026-05-28): both are mutually
   recursive ŌĆö `present`/`absent`/`open` carry a `Type`, and Type's
   `effects_rows` carries an `EffectExpression`. Splitting them into two
   files created a cross-file import cycle; colocating them removes it.

   NOTE: wiring `Type.arrow.effects` (and `Function.E`) to carry an
   `EffectExpression` instead of `List[Type]`, and the row-unification that
   checks it, is the implementation step tracked by WI-307; this sort is the
   agreed representation it targets. >}
enum anthill.prelude.EffectExpression
  import anthill.prelude.{List}
  import anthill.reflect.{Term}

  -- `{}` ŌĆö the closed empty row (pure: nothing present, no open tail).
  -- Named `empty_row` (not `empty`) to avoid colliding with the various
  -- `Collection`/`Map`/`Set`/`LogicalStream` `empty` operations.
  entity empty_row

  -- a single present effect label, e.g. `Modify[c]` (the `e` / `+e` form;
  -- listing a label means presence). `label` is the effect Type ŌĆö term-backed
  -- `Fn{Modify, named:[(<param>, TypeExtractor.Denoted(c))]}` (WI-361).
  entity present(label: Type)

  -- `e :- g` ŌĆö a CONDITIONAL (guarded) present effect (proposal 048): present
  -- iff its guard `g` is not refuted at the call site. `label` is the effect
  -- Type (as in `present`); `guard` is the guard's Horn body ŌĆö a CONJUNCTION of
  -- goal terms over the operation's parameters (`[eq(b, 0)]` for `Int64.div`;
  -- `[p(a), q(b)]` for a `( E :- p(a), q(b) )` element), mirroring `rule_body`.
  -- Discharge ŌĆö refuting the conjunction from the call context ŌĆö DROPS the
  -- element (ŌåÆ `{}`); an unrefuted guard keeps it (ŌåÆ `present`), so the row stays
  -- a sound over-approximation. `present(label)` is the degenerate empty-guard
  -- (`:- true`) case. Per-element by construction (the guard binds ONE label), so
  -- a row freely mixes guarded and unguarded elements; two `guarded` atoms on one
  -- label are the unreduced `g1 Ōł© g2` merge-join, and subtyping is guard
  -- entailment (`g1 ŌŖ© g2`) ŌĆö see proposal 048 ┬¦"Lattice of guarded rows".
  entity guarded(label: Type, guard: List[Term])

  -- `- e` ŌĆö a guaranteed-absent effect: a `lacks` constraint on the tail.
  -- The only load-bearing marker, since presence is the default.
  entity absent(label: Type)

  -- an open row tail: a row variable `E` / `?`, carried as a `Type.type_var`.
  -- An open row absorbs extra actual labels (covariant-effects subtyping);
  -- a closed expression (no `open`) does not. `effects E = ?` binds one.
  entity open(tail: Type)

  -- `merge(x, y)` ŌĆö union of two expressions; the set literal `{ E1, ŌĆ”, EN }`
  -- is iterated `merge` (pure sugar). A present/absent clash on the same
  -- label is a row-unification failure, not a propagating value (045 ┬¦7.2).
  entity merge(left: EffectExpression, right: EffectExpression)

  fact PartialEq[T = EffectExpression]   -- WI-644: Eq requires the PartialEq base
  fact Eq[T = EffectExpression]
end

-- Standalone records used by `TypeExtractor` ŌĆö kept OUTSIDE the enum (so the
-- Rust bootstrap emits them as structs usable as `Vec<TypeBinding>` /
-- `Vec<NamedTupleElement>`), and as top-level qualified-name entities (so they
-- land in the same Rust module scope as the qualified-name enums beside them).
-- `param`/`value` of a binding, `name`/`type` of a tuple element.
entity anthill.prelude.TypeBinding(param: anthill.reflect.Symbol, value: anthill.reflect.Term)
entity anthill.prelude.NamedTupleElement(name: anthill.reflect.Symbol, type: anthill.reflect.Term)

{< TypeExtractor: the reified deep structure of a `Type`.

   A `Type` *value* is term-backed (the engine stores it as an ordinary term ŌĆö
   `Ref(S)` for a bare sort, `Fn{S, named}` for a parameterized type, with a
   value-in-type carried as `denoted`). This enum is NOT that stored form ŌĆö it
   is what `anthill.reflect.extract(t)` REIFIES on demand so a program can
   `case` over a type's structure. The variants mirror the structural forms a
   type can take; `extract` reads the term backing into exactly one of them.
   Nothing here is stored ŌĆö the deep representation is a computed view, defined
   once in the stdlib (the Rust engine view is generated from this). >}
enum anthill.prelude.TypeExtractor
  import anthill.prelude.{List}
  import anthill.reflect.{Symbol, NodeOccurrence, Term}

  entity SortRef(name: Symbol)
  entity TypeVar(name: Symbol)
  entity Parameterized(base: Symbol, bindings: List[TypeBinding])
  entity Arrow(param: Term, result: Term, effects: Term)
  entity Denoted(value: NodeOccurrence)
  {< WI-376: an expression-carried type projection `s.T` / `s.Sort`. `value` is the
     RECEIVER occurrence (a param/local ref, or any typed expression); `member` is the
     projected type-member name (`T`, `Sort`, `E`). The type-member sibling of
     `Denoted` (a value-in-type, which STAYS): this is ELIMINATED at the unify boundary
     by projecting the receiver's synthesized type. A ground (ref) receiver rides as a
     hash-consed term `Fn{ExprCarried, value: Ref(s), member: Ref(M)}`. >}
  entity ExprCarried(value: NodeOccurrence, member: Symbol)
  {< WI-428: a RIGID type-receiver projection `P.Key` / `MemStore.Key` ŌĆö the type-keyed
     sibling of `ExprCarried` (docs/design/path-dependent-types.md ┬¦5.3). `var` is the
     projection SUBJECT: a type-parameter reference (rigid ŌĆö stays a neutral until the
     parameter is instantiated) or a concrete sort ref (manifest ŌĆö ╬┤-grounds at the
     elimination site and never survives as a stored type). `sort` is the sort whose
     `requires` chain lends the subject its members (= the subject itself for a
     concrete-sort subject). `member` is the projected member NAME, resolved against the
     bound spec's declared params (a positional spec application is sugar for names).
     The canonical bound-APPLICATION slot (`requires`, design ┬¦5.3) is
     deferred-equivalent in v1: a subject with several candidate bounds is a loud
     ambiguity error, so `(var, member)` determines the bound uniquely; the slot lands
     with multi-bound support. >}
  entity RigidTypeProjection(sort: Symbol, var: Term, member: Symbol)
  -- The wrapped EffectExpression. Field name `effects_expr` (not `expr`) so the
  -- relocated structural functor's stored term ŌĆö `Fn{TypeExtractor.EffectsRows,
  -- named:[(effects_expr, ŌĆ”)]}`, built by `make_effects_rows_type` ŌĆö matches this
  -- declaration directly (WI-361; the engine uses `effects_expr` throughout).
  entity EffectsRows(effects_expr: EffectExpression)
  entity NamedTuple(fields: List[NamedTupleElement])
  entity Nothing
  {< The term is not a well-formed type ŌĆö `extract` could not classify it (a
     non-type term, or a malformed type expression). Keeps `extract` total
     rather than returning an `Option`. `term` is the offending input. >}
  entity Error(term: Term)
end
